    <para id="id1167779965873">Equation (1) has a zero at infinity and a pole at <figure id="id1167778603363"><media id="id1167778603363_media" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/graphics5-e4e1.png" id="id1167778603363__onlineimage" height="21" width="20"/></media></figure><emphasis effect="bold">. </emphasis>Hence it has -20dB asymptote at <figure id="id1167781030817"><media id="id1167781030817_media" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/graphics6-e1ad.png" id="id1167781030817__onlineimage" height="21" width="19"/></media></figure> . This gives 100% transmission below <figure id="id1167776250508"><media id="id1167776250508_media" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/graphics7-e85e.png" id="id1167776250508__onlineimage" height="21" width="22"/></media></figure> and suppression of frequencies higher than <figure id="id1167776178766"><media id="id1167776178766_media" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/graphics8-e1ad.png" id="id1167776178766__onlineimage" height="21" width="19"/></media></figure> at the rate of 20dB per decade as we move up the frequency scale .</para>
    <para id="id1167777411941">The Time-Domain Response at high frequencies and Frequency Response of a LPF are related to each other through the relation: <figure id="id1167775822129"><media id="id1167775822129_media" alt=""><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/Picture 4-0372.png" id="id1167775822129__onlineimage" height="32" width="122"/></media></figure></para>
